Direct Known Subclasses:
DragMove, DragStart, DragStop, MouseMove
public abstract class Position<T>
extends Widget.Event<T>

An abstract type of high level events that may be fired from a source widget when the mouse has position data to report to the element wrapped by the widget.

This class is designed generic with the type parameter being the type of its corresponding listener type. A subclass must be concrete and final if it is to be an event type. As an event type, the subclass must also declare the type parameter of this class as the type of its own listener.

An event listener is typically of an interface with a declared method to react on the event it handles so that the class of the event can implement the Source.Event.execute(Object) method by simply calling that declared method passing the event itself as the argument. A subclass of this class defines events uniquely typed by the subclass itself and designates a listener type corresponding to that type of events.

For an event source to fire an event, the listener of the event must have been registered onto the source object with a call to the Source.addListener(Class, Object) method which asks both the type of the event and the listener object for arguments.

Note that, high level events are Configurable.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org

Field Detail

X

public static final Id<java.lang.Number> X

A global identifier for a configurable property of a Position object.

The identified configurable property of a Position object refers to an integer value specifying the X coordinate of the mouse position, in pixels when the event is fired.

Since:
1.0

Constructor Detail

Position

protected Position(Component target,
                   java.lang.Number x,
                   java.lang.Number y)

Constructs an event of this type.

This constructor simply invokes the default constructor of the superclass and sets its configurable property Widget.Event.TARGET to the first argument, X to the second, and Y to the third.

Note that, this constructor does not change the configurable properties Source.Event.BUBBLE and Source.Event.UPDATE.

Parameters:
target - A related mouse target when this event is fired.
x - The X coordinate, in pixels, of the mouse position.
y - The y coordinate, in pixels, of the mouse position.
Since:
1.0
